Building Dashboards for Bank Credit Risk Analyses

Last week, we started building the Bank Credit Risk Analyses Dashboards. We created frequency distributions and plotted either the barchart or pie chart for categorical variables and histograms for numerical variables. We plotted the scatterplot to compare relationship of two variables and conducted the Pareto Analyses on Customer Savings This week we will continue to build on the Dashboards by adding statistical measures, goodness of fit and outlier analyses.

1) Preparation

- Start by installing the packges you need. I will set message=FALSE and warning=FALSE so they will not show up in the HTML output.

Install Packages

#install.packages("psych") #only need to run this code once to install the package
library("dplyr") #need to call the libary before you use the package
library("tidyr")
library("rpivotTable")
library("knitr")
library("psych")

Set Working Directory and Importing Data

The worksheet Base Data in the Excel file Bank Credit Risk Data provides information about 425 bank customers who had applied for loans. Each of the column is defined as follows:

  • Loan Purpose : Type of purpose for the loan applied
  • Checking : Checking account balance
  • Savings : Savings account balance
  • Months Customer: Number of months has been a customer of the bank
  • Months Employed: Number of months in employment
  • Gender: Gender
  • Marital Status: Marital status
  • Age: Age in years
  • Housing: Housing type
  • Years: Number of years at current residence
  • Job: Job type
  • Credit Risk: Credit-risk classification by the bank

- Be sure to set working directory and import the datafile.

#put in your working directory folder pathname

                               sheet = "Base Data", skip = 2)

# for Coefficient of Skewness and Kurtosis used in R is Type 3 default - 
# which is similar to the formulas in our text and lecture notes. 
# However for Kurtosis, the formula in R is less by 3. The interpretation is also adjusted such that
# for kurtosis >0 means distribution has high peaks and skinny tails.
# while kurtosis  <0 means distribution has low peak and heavy tails.
cs.age<-(sum((BD$Age-mean(BD$Age))**3)/nrow(BD))/(sd(BD$Age))**3
print(c("Coefficient of Skewness (Age): ", cs.age))
## [1] "Coefficient of Skewness (Age): " "0.96099476005924"
ck.age<-(sum((BD$Age-mean(BD$Age))**4)/nrow(BD))/((sd(BD$Age))**4)
print(c("Coefficient of Kurtosis (Age): ", ck.age))
## [1] "Coefficient of Kurtosis (Age): " "3.40347777399678"
cs.save<-(sum((BD$Savings-mean(BD$Savings))**3)/nrow(BD))/(sd(BD$Savings))**3
print(c("Coefficient of Skewness (Savings): ", cs.save))
## [1] "Coefficient of Skewness (Savings): " "3.01122071874119"
ck.save<-(sum((BD$Savings-mean(BD$Savings))**4)/nrow(BD))/((sd(BD$Savings))**4)
print(c("Coefficient of Kurtosis (Savings): ", ck.save))
## [1] "Coefficient of Kurtosis (Savings): " "11.7630268258091"
dfage <- describe(BD$Age, IQR=TRUE)
dfsavings <- describe(BD$Savings, IQR=TRUE)
df.desc1<-rbind(dfage,dfsavings)

ii) Linear relationship between age and savings

# plot a scatterplot
plot(BD$Age,BD$Savings, main="Scatterplot of Savings to Age", xlab="Age", ylab="Savings", pch=18)

#no clear pattern btw the two variables as alot of points are cluttered at the bottom. 

# Now we compute statistical measures to assess the extent of linear correlation
# compute Covariance of Age and Savings
cov.AS<-cov(BD$Age, BD$Savings)
print("Covariance: ")
## [1] "Covariance: "
cov.AS
## [1] -1123.868
#Compute Pearson's Correlation Coefficient for Age and Savings
cor.AS <- cor(BD$Age, BD$Savings)
print ("Correlation Coefficient of Age and Savings: ")
## [1] "Correlation Coefficient of Age and Savings: "

## [1] -0.02828589

i) Frequency Distribution/ Charts for Loan Purpose by Customer Gender (Categorical)

# Create contingency table for loan purpose and gender with loan purpose as columns and gender as rows
BD3 <- BD %>% group_by(`Loan Purpose`,Gender) %>% tally()
BD3.spread<- BD3 %>% spread(key=`Loan Purpose`,value=n)
BD3.spread[is.na(BD3.spread)]<-0 #convert NA to 0 value

Since both variables are categorical variables, we will use the grouped bar chart to compare frequencies across of loan types across each gender type (female and male). From the charts, we can see frequency of loans are generally higher for MALES compared to FEMALES, regardless of type of loans (except for Education).

D) Customer Savings Outlier Analyses Dashboard

Purpose: To conduct outlier analyses on savings

i) Check distribution of Savings

# Conduct Shapiro-Wilkins Test 
shapiro.test(BD$Savings)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  BD$Savings
## W = 0.51006, p-value < 2.2e-16
# Since data is not normally distributed, we can use Chebyshev's Theorem to identify data that is within 3 sd of the mean. Then use Z-scores > +3 or < -3 for outlier identification

boxplot(BD$Savings, horizontal=TRUE) #applying 1.5*IQR to the left of Q1 or right of Q3

boxplot(BD$Savings, horizontal=TRUE, range=3 ) #applying 3*IQR to the left of Q1 or right of Q3




Building Dashboards for Food Order Demand

This dataset comprises of 105 daily food order demand data for a restaurant. Each of the column is defined as follows:

  • Day : A running number indicating the day from when data was captured, ie 1 indicate Day 1, 2 indicates Day 2.
  • Demand : Number of food orders for the day

Lets build a simple dashboard for the restaurant with this data

2) Plot the data using histogram, boxplot and line chart

# Plot the Histogram 
hist(D$Demand, main="Histogram of Daily Demand", xlab = "Demand")

# Use Shapiro-Wilkins Test to test if data is normally distributed
shapiro.test(D$Demand)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  D$Demand
## W = 0.56684, p-value = 4.248e-16
# Plot boxplot to view the distribution of the data, and if outlier exists
boxplot(D$Demand, horizontal=TRUE, xlab="Demand (1.5 IQR)", range=1.5) #applying 1.5*IQR to the left of Q1 or right of Q3

boxplot(D$Demand, horizontal=TRUE, xlab="Demand (3 IQR)", range = 3) #applying 3*IQR to the left of Q1 or right of Q3 

# Plot line chart of Daily demand over time
plot(D$Day, D$Demand, main="Daily Demand in Food Orders", ylab="Demand", xlab="Day")
lines(D$Day, D$Demand)

3) Identify and remove outliers

# Let pull out the outliers from the data. 
# From the chart, it looks quite clear that values => 1500 could count as outliers. 

D.outlier<- D %>% filter(Demand>=1500) # this df contains just the outliers
D.wo<- D %>% filter(Demand<1500) # this df is without the outliers 


# now let's run the same plots and analyses without the outliers. 
hist(D.wo$Demand)

##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test

## data:  D.wo$Demand
## W = 0.9956, p-value = 0.9877

4) Impute outliers with mean

# Another way to handle outliers is to impute with mean data.
D$Demand.imp <- D$Demand
D$Demand.imp[D$Demand>=1500]<-mean(D$Demand)

5) Dashboard with imputed data

i) now lets run the same plots and analyses with imputed mean data for outliers.

hist(D$Demand.imp)

# Other graphical methods to check for normality: 1) Density plot 2) Q-Q plot
# Density Plot (smoothed version of the histogram)
plot(density(D$Demand.imp))

# Q-Q plot (draws the correlation between a given sample and the normal distribution. A 45-degree reference line is also plotted)
qqnorm(D$Demand.imp)
qqline(D$Demand.imp)

iii) Computing Probabilities using the imputed data

Lets try to compute the following probabilities: 1) Demand > 800, 2) Demand < 550, 3) 700 < Demand < 800 Using empirical data to compute probabilities

# 1) Demand.imp > 800
d1<- D %>% filter(Demand.imp>800)
pr1 <- nrow(d1)/nrow(D)  
print ("Probabilty of Demand > 800: ")
## [1] "Probabilty of Demand > 800: "
pr1
## [1] 0.1428571
# 2) Demand.imp < 550 
d2<-D %>% filter(Demand.imp<550 )
pr2 <- nrow(d2)/nrow(D)  
print ("Probabilty of Demand < 550: ")
## [1] "Probabilty of Demand < 550: "
pr2
## [1] 0.03809524
# 3) 700 < Demand.imp < 800
d3<-D %>% filter(Demand.imp<800 & Demand.imp>700)
pr3 <- nrow(d3)/nrow(D)  
print ("Probabilty of 700< Demand < 800: ")
## [1] "Probabilty of 700< Demand < 800: "
pr3
## [1] 0.4095238

What if we dont have the raw demand data. Instead we have summary data of the mean and std deviation for demand. We are also told that demand is normally distributed. How can we compute the above probabilities using the standard normal distribution

m<-mean(D$Demand.imp)
s<-sd(D$Demand.imp)

# 1) Demand.imp > 800
pr11<-pnorm(800,mean=m, sd=s, lower.tail = FALSE)
print ("Probabilty of Demand > 800: ")
## [1] "Probabilty of Demand > 800: "
pr11
## [1] 0.1617192
# 2) Demand.imp < 550 
pr22 <- pnorm(550,mean=m, sd=s, lower.tail = TRUE)  
print ("Probabilty of Demand < 550: ")
## [1] "Probabilty of Demand < 550: "
pr22
## [1] 0.03262197
# 3) 700 < Demand.imp < 800
pr33 <- pnorm(800,mean=m, sd=s, lower.tail = TRUE) - pnorm(700,mean=m, sd=s, lower.tail = TRUE)
print ("Probabilty of 700< Demand < 800: ")
## [1] "Probabilty of 700< Demand < 800: "
pr33
## [1] 0.3959187
